               <msContents>

                  <summary source="#allegro">Fragment of the First Document of Breathing, a Late
                     Egyptian funerary text securing the afterlife of the deceased.</summary>
                  <textLang mainLang="egy-Egyh" source="#TM">Egyptian in Hieratic script</textLang>



               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <p>Written along the fibres with some text lost at the beginning together with the
                     owner's name. The papyrus is mounted on paper in a glass frame and its back is
                     not visible.</p>
                  <objectDesc form="scroll">
                     <supportDesc material="papyrus">
                        <support>papyrus</support>
                        <extent>One large fragment of papyrus.<dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>1240</height>
                              <width>285</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout>Written in seven columns, four of which survive almost fully and three are
                           severely damaged.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote>Likely written by one scribe, all in black ink.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote>A series of vignettes in line drawing, placed across the top of the
                        seven columns hieratic writing, originally covered the complete length of
                        the manuscript. The surviving scenes include a
                        human-headed ba-bird seated on a socle; Anubis holding the mummy upright;
                        the tree goddess bringing a libation offering;the Weighing of the Heart;
                        and four standing demons holding a knife in the left and the sign of life
                        in their right hands.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>

               </physDesc>
